         SECTION [section number]

           Sets or increments the current  section  number.  If  the  section
           number is omitted, then the subsection number at the current level
           is incremented.  If the section number is given, it is taken to be
           the  new  section  number, and the current level is set to the the
           number of subsections in the section number.

           Section numbers are of the form:
               [integer [.integer [.integer]...  ]]
           A section number like "2" (integer) is a level 1  section  number,                                                    _____ _
           "3.4.0"  (integer.integer.integer)  is  a  level 3 section number,                                                      _____ _
           etc.  The SECTION  command  without  a  specified  section  number
           increments the number associated with the current level only.  For                                                     _______ _____
           example, if the section number is "3.4.0" when a  SECTION  command
           is  given,  then  it  will  become  "3.4.1".  Here  are a few more
           examples:

                     section = 2.0.9
                $SECTION
                     section = 2.0.10
                $LEVEL +1
                     section = 2.0.10.0
                $SECTION 3.3
                     section = 3.3
                $LEVEL 4
                     section = 3.3.0.0
                $LEVEL -3
                     section = 3

           The character pair ^# is translated by  SCRIBE  into  the  current                              __
           section  number  whenever  it is encountered.  The CONTROL command
           has no effect on this translation.  If the  characters,  "^#"  are
           desired in the output text, type "^^#".

         SKIP [integer]

           Causes SCRIBE to output the number of blank lines specified by the
           integer.  If no integer is given, one blank line will  be  output.
           If an integer greater than 1 is given, SCRIBE will not skip beyond
           the top of the next page.  Also, a  SKIP  encountered  immediately
           after  a  page break not forced by a PAGE command will be ignored,                                ___
           to avoid the printing of spurious lines at the top of pages.

         SPACING [integer]

           Specifies the  inter-line  spacing  (the  number  of  blank  lines
           between   printed   text   lines).   $SPACING   1  corresponds  to
           single-spacing (no blank lines),  $SPACING  2  to  double-spacing,
           etc.

           SCRIBE defaults to single-spacing.



                                       - 9 -






       SCRIBE-10 Manual
       Version 3.0  18-August-78


         TABS [integer [[,] integer]...  ]

           Specifies  successive  column  positions  for  tabs (control-I) in
           verbatim mode.  In all other modes, tabs are  completely  ignored,           ________
           i.e.,  they  are  discarded.  As one might expect, tabs are useful
           for preparing tables to be printed  verbatim.  Tab  positions  are
           relative to the left margin as defined by $MARGIN, $INDENT, and/or           ________
           $PARAGRAPH.  Thus, if the first defined tab stop is  5,  the  left
           indentation  is 2, and the margin 5, the first tab stop will be at
           absolute column 12.  The fact that tabs are relative allows tables
           to  be shifted left or right without affecting the relative column
           positions.  Unfortunately, tab positions are not settable  on  the
           PDP/10, and are always printed at intervals of 8 characters.  This
           makes table preparation with tabs more of a chore, as  you  cannot
           see what the tables will actually look like when editing, but must
           run the document through SCRIBE.  When beyond the last  tab  stop,
           or if no tabs are specified, a tab is printed as a single space in
           verbatim mode.

           SCRIBE defaults to no defined tab stops.  To return to the default
           state, type $TABS by itself.

         TOC

           Includes all of the entries previously stored by ENTRY commands at
           the point of the TOC (Table  of  Contents)  command.  The  storage                                 _      _   _
           used  to  hold  the  entries is then cleared.  A standard table of
           contents can be made rather easily by doing the following:

              After each $SECTION and $LEVEL command, give the command
                  $ENTRY '^# <tab> <section name> <tab> \'

              Then, at the end of the input file, the command sequence

                  $TABS 10,60
                  $VERBATIM
                  $SPACING 2
                  SECTION <tab> <tab> PAGE

                  $TOC

              will produce the desired table of contents.

         TRANSLATE [ <string1> <string2> ]

           Causes SCRIBE to translate characters occuring in  <string1>  into
           the   corresponding   characters  in  <string2>.  $TRA  '|+'  '\&'
           translates all vertical bars into backslashes, and all plus  signs
           to ampersands.

           <string1> must be at least as long as <string2>; characters at the
           end of <string1> with no corresponding characters in <string2> are
           left   alone.  A  TRANSLATE  command  with  no  strings  specified


